graphicslib3D

Class GeometryTransformPipeline

  • java.lang.Object
    • graphicslib3D.GeometryTransformPipeline

  • public class GeometryTransformPipeline
extends java.lang.Object
    This class manages a set of global ModelView and Projection MatrixStacks comprising the geometry transformation pipeline. It maintains internal copies of MatrixStacks for each of MV and P, and allows clients to set the values for these stacks and to get either the top elements of the stacks or the entire stack. This allows a client class to create MV and P matrix stacks which are then accessible (via static methods) to other classes. The class also provides methods for obtaining combined ModelView and Projection matrices, and for obtaining the so-called Normal Matrix corresponding to the transformation at the top of the ModelView stack.
    Author:
    John Clevenger

      • getModelViewProjectionMatrix

        public static Matrix3D getModelViewProjectionMatrix()
        Returns a new Matrix3D which is the concatenation of the top of the current ModelView MatrixStack with the top of the current Projection MatrixStack. The returned Matrix3D is formed by concatenating the MV matrix on the right of the P matrix, as 

           returnVal = currentProjMatrix X currentModelViewMatrix ;
        Returns:
        the current ModelViewProjection matrix

      • getNormalMatrix

        public static Matrix3D getNormalMatrix(boolean renormalize)
        Returns the Normal Matrix corresponding to ModelView matrix at the top of the ModelView stack. The Normal Matrix is defined as the transpose of the inverse of the rotational component of the ModelView matrix; this is the matrix required to transform a vector in the same way that the current ModelView matrix transforms a point.

        The method assumes by default that the rotational component of the ModelView matrix is orthogonal; i.e. that no non-uniform scaling has been applied to the ModelView matrix. If non-uniform scaling (that is, scaling by a different amount in any of X, Y, or Z) has been applied, the method can be told to renormalize (orthogonalize) the rotational component by passing true as the input parameter. Note that passing true causes increased computations; if it is known that the ModelView matrix is already orthogonal (doesn't contain any non-uniform scaling) then false should be specified.

        In any case the method does not alter the original contents of the ModelView matrix.

        Parameters:
        renormalize - - true to force the method to normalize (make orthogonal) the rotational component; false if the rotational component is known to already be orthogonal
        Returns:
        a Matrix3D containing the Normal Matrix corresponding to the top of the ModelView stack
